When you see a collection of child objects owned by a parent, that means there&#39;s a one-to-many relationship between the entities. You&#39;ll need parent and child tables, with a foreign key relationship to the parent in the child table. There will be zero or more rows in the child table for each row in the parent table.

You have it right in your design.  There&#39;s no need for the `order` table to know about the `orderItem` table.  The child table needs to [refer][1] to the parent.

    CREATE TABLE order (
        id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
        id_person INT FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES person(id),;
    );
    
    CREATE TABLE orderItem (
        id INT AUTO_INCREENT PRIMARY KEY,
        id_product INT FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES product(id),
        quantity INT(999999) NOT NULL,
        id_order INT FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES order(id)
    );


  [1]: https://www.w3schools.com/sql/sql_foreignkey.asp

